Definition 1.1. We define a triangulated category of singularities of $X,$ denoted by ${\mathbf{D}}_{\rm Sg}({X}),$ as the quotient of the triangulated category ${\mathbf{D}}^{b}({\operatorname{coh}X})$ by the full triangulated subcategory ${\mathfrak{P}}{\mathfrak{e}}{\mathfrak{r}}{\mathfrak{f}}({X}).$
Definition 3.1. We say that $f$ is an isomorphism infinitely near $Z$ if it is flat over $Z$ and the fiber product $Z^{\prime}=Z\times_{X}X^{\prime}$ is isomorphic to $Z.$
Definition 1.4. Let $X$ be a set and ${\mathcal{C}}=\{C_{0},\ldots,C_{N}\}$ be a finite covering of $X$. The covering ${\mathcal{C}}$ viewed as a subbasis for closed sets induces a topology on $X$. The space $X$ together with the topology induced from ${\mathcal{C}}$ is denoted by $(X,{\mathcal{C}})$.
Definition 1.2. Let $X$ and ${\mathcal{C}}$ be as before. We use $(X,\prec_{\mathcal{C}})$ to denote the set $X$ with its Alexandrov topology induced from the preorder relation $\prec_{\mathcal{C}}$ defined above.
Definition 2.6. Category $\widetilde{{\mathcal{A}ux}}$ is a category whose objects are the same as in ${\mathcal{O}\mathcal{C}ov}_{\rm fin}$ and ${\mathcal{A}ux}$. Morphisms in $\widetilde{{\mathcal{A}ux}}$ are pairs of the form $(f,\alpha):(A,\underline{\Pi})\rightarrow(A^{\prime},\underline{\Pi}^{\prime})$, where $\alpha\in\mathcal{M}$ and $f:\check{\alpha}(A,\underline{\Pi})\longrightarrow(A^{\prime},\underline{\Pi}^% {\prime})$ is a morphism in ${\mathcal{O}\mathcal{C}ov}_{\rm fin}$. The identity morphisms are simply $(\operatorname{\rm id}_{A},\operatorname{\rm id}_{\mathbb{N}})$, and the composition of morphisms is defined as $(g,\beta)\circ(f,\alpha)=(g\circ(\check{\beta}f),\alpha\circ\beta).$
Definition 2.10. The objects of ${\widetilde{{\rm Sh}}}_{\rm fin}({\mathbb{P}^{\infty}\!({{\mathbb{Z}}/2})})$ are finitely-supported flabby sheaves of algebras over ${\mathbb{P}^{\infty}\!({{\mathbb{Z}}/2})}$. A morphism $[\tilde{f},\alpha^{*}]:P\rightarrow Q$ in ${\widetilde{{\rm Sh}}}_{\rm fin}({\mathbb{P}^{\infty}\!({{\mathbb{Z}}/2})})$ is a pair consisting of a continuous map (see (22)) $\alpha^{*}:{\mathbb{P}^{\infty}\!({{\mathbb{Z}}/2})}\longrightarrow{\mathbb{P}% ^{\infty}\!({{\mathbb{Z}}/2})},\quad\chi_{a}\longmapsto\chi_{\alpha^{-1}(a)},$ where $\mathcal{M}\ni\alpha:{\mathbb{N}}\rightarrow{\mathbb{N}}$ is a tame surjection (Definition 1.17), and a morphism of sheaves $\tilde{f}:\alpha^{*}_{*}P\rightarrow Q.$ Composition of morphisms is given by $[\tilde{g},\beta^{*}]\circ[\tilde{f},\alpha^{*}]:=[\tilde{g}\circ(\beta^{*}_{*% }\tilde{f}),\beta^{*}\circ\alpha^{*}].$
Definition 1.12. ${\mathbb{P}^{\infty}\!({{\mathbb{Z}}/2})}:={\rm colimit}_{N\geqslant 0}{% \mathbb{P}^{N}\!({{\mathbb{Z}}/2})}$.
Definition 2.2. Let ${\mathcal{C}ov}_{\rm fin}$ be a category whose objects are pairs $(A,\Pi)$, where $A$ is a unital algebra and $\Pi$ is a finite set of unital algebra epimorphisms that is a covering of the algebra $A$. A morphism $f\colon(A,\Pi)\to(A^{\prime},\Pi^{\prime})$ in this category is a morphism of algebras $f\colon A\to A^{\prime}$ satisfying the condition that for any epimorphism $\pi^{\prime}_{i}\colon A^{\prime}\to A^{\prime}_{i}$ in the covering $\Pi^{\prime}$ there exists an epimorphism $\pi_{j}\colon A\to A_{j}$ in the covering $\Pi$ such that $\ker(\pi_{j})\subseteq f^{-1}(\ker(\pi^{\prime}_{i}))$. This category will be called the category of finite coverings of algebras.
Definition 1.1. Let $X$ be a set and let ${\mathcal{C}}=\{C_{0},\ldots,C_{N}\}$ be a finite covering of $X$, i.e., let $\bigcup{\mathcal{C}}:=\bigcup_{i}C_{i}=X$. For any $x\in X$, we define its support $supp_{\mathcal{C}}(x)=\{C\in{\mathcal{C}}|\ x\in C\}$. A preorder $\prec_{\mathcal{C}}$ on $X$ is defined by $x\prec_{\mathcal{C}}y$ if and only if $supp_{\mathcal{C}}(x)\supseteq supp_{\mathcal{C}}(y)$. We also define an equivalence relation $\sim_{\mathcal{C}}$ by letting $x\sim_{\mathcal{C}}y$ if and only if $supp_{\mathcal{C}}(x)=supp_{\mathcal{C}}(y)$. Note that $\prec_{{\mathcal{C}}}$ induces on $X/\!\!\sim_{\mathcal{C}}$ a partial order. This space is called the partition space associated with the finite covering ${\mathcal{C}}$ of $X$.
Definition 2.3. Category ${\mathcal{A}ux}$ is a category whose objects are the same as the objects of ${\mathcal{O}\mathcal{C}ov}_{\rm fin}$. A morphism $f\colon(A,\underline{\Pi})\to(A^{\prime},\underline{\Pi}^{\prime})$ in ${\mathcal{A}ux}$ is a morphism of algebras $f\colon A\to A^{\prime}$ satisfying the property that for every $\pi_{j}^{\prime}$ appearing in the sequence $\underline{\Pi}^{\prime}$ there exists an epimorphism $\pi_{i}$ appearing in the ordered sequence $\underline{\Pi}$ such that $\ker(\pi_{i})\subseteq f^{-1}(\ker(\pi_{j}^{\prime}))$.
Definition 1.17. A surjection $\alpha\colon{\mathbb{N}}\to{\mathbb{N}}$ is called tame if (1) $\alpha^{-1}(i)$ is finite for any $i\in{\mathbb{N}}$, (2) $|\alpha^{-1}(i)|>1$ for finitely many $i\in{\mathbb{N}}$. We denote the monoid of all such tame surjections by ${\mathcal{M}}$.
Definition 3.2. We define the C*-algebra $C({{\mathbb{P}}^{N}(\mathcal{T})})$ as the limit of the diagram: $\xymatrix@R=2mm@C=0.15cm{0&\ldots&i&\ldots&j&\ldots&N\\ {{\mathcal{T}}^{\otimes{N}}}&\ldots&{{\mathcal{T}}^{\otimes{N}}}\ar[dddd]_{% \sigma_{j}}&\ldots&\!\!\!\!\!\!{{\mathcal{T}}^{\otimes{N}}}\ar@<-2ex>[dddd]^{% \sigma_{i+1}}&\ldots&{{\mathcal{T}}^{\otimes{N}}}\\ {\ }\\ {\ }\\ {\ }\\ \ldots&\ldots&{{\mathcal{T}}^{\otimes{j-1}}}\otimes{C(S^{1})}\otimes{{\mathcal% {T}}^{\otimes{N-j}}}&&{{\mathcal{T}}^{\otimes{i}}}\otimes{C(S^{1})}\otimes{{% \mathcal{T}}^{\otimes{N-i-1}}}\ar[ll]_{\Psi_{ij}}&\ldots&\ldots\;.}$ Here $\sigma_{k}:=\operatorname{\rm id}_{{{\mathcal{T}}^{\otimes{k-1}}}}\otimes% \sigma\otimes\operatorname{\rm id}_{{{\mathcal{T}}^{\otimes{N-k}}}}$. We call $\,{{\mathbb{P}}^{N}(\mathcal{T})}$ a $\,$Toeplitz quantum complex projective space.
Definition 2.1. ${\mathcal{O}\mathcal{C}ov}_{\rm fin}:={\rm colim}_{N}\boldsymbol{C}_{N}$. The category ${\mathcal{O}\mathcal{C}ov}_{\rm fin}$ is called the category of finite ordered coverings of algebras.
Definition 1.10. For any $i\in\underline{N}$ and any non-empty subset $a\subseteq\underline{N}$, we define open sets ${\mathbb{A}}_{i}^{N}=\{(z_{0},\ldots,z_{N})\in({{\mathbb{Z}}/2})^{N+1}\;|\;z_{% i}=1\}={\uparrow\!\!\chi}_{\{i\}}\quad\text{ and }\quad{\mathbb{A}}^{N}_{a}:=% \bigcap_{i\in a}{\mathbb{A}}_{i}^{N}={\uparrow\!\!\chi}_{a}\;.$ For brevity, when there is no risk of confusion we omit the superscripts and write ${\mathbb{A}}_{i}$ and ${\mathbb{A}}_{a}$ instead of ${\mathbb{A}}_{i}^{N}$ and ${\mathbb{A}}_{a}^{N}$.
Definition 2.8. A flabby sheaf $F\in Ob({\rm Sh}({\mathbb{P}^{\infty}\!({{\mathbb{Z}}/2})}))$ is said to have finite support if there exists $N\in{\mathbb{N}}$ such that $F({\mathbb{A}}_{n})=0$ for any $n>N$. The full subcategory of flabby sheaves with finite support will be denoted by ${\rm Sh}_{\rm fin}({\mathbb{P}^{\infty}\!({{\mathbb{Z}}/2})})$.
Definition 1.2 A morphism of PERs $f:R\to S$, is a function $f:\mathrm{dom}R/R\to\mathrm{dom}S/S$, which is tracked by a partial recursive function. This means that there is a partial recursive function $\phi$ such that for all $n\in\mathrm{dom}R$ $\phi n$ is defined and $f[n]_{R}=[\phi n]_{S}$.
Definition 2.2 A realizable endofunctor $F$ of the category of PERs is monotone, if its object map is monotone with respect to the inclusion ordering on PERs. In other words: if $R\subset S$, then $FR\subset FS$.
Definition 1.1 A PER is a partial equivalence relation on the natural numbers. So a PER $R$ is a subset of $\mathbb{N}^{2}$ such that: • for all $(n,m)\in\mathbb{N}$, $(m,n)\in\mathbb{N}$ (symmetry) • for all $(n,m)$ and $(m,p)\in\mathbb{N}$, $(n,p)\in\mathbb{N}$ (transitivity)
Definition 2.1 An endofunctor $F$ of the category of PERs is realizable, if there is a single partial recursive function $\phi$ that tracks $F:\hom(R,S)\to\hom(FR,FS)$ for all $R$ and $S$. This means that $\phi x$ converges whenever $[x]:R\to S$ for every pair of PERs $R$ and $S$, and that $F([x]_{R\to S})=[\phi x]_{FR\to FS}$ We say that $\phi$ tracks $F$ is this case.
Definition 1.5. (the solution set conditions) Let $\mathcal{C}$ be a category, $\mathsf{W}$ a class of morphisms, $m\in\operatorname{mor}\mathcal{C}$. Say that $\mathsf{W}$ satisfies the solution set condition at $m$ if there exists a subset $\mathsf{W}_{m}$ of $\mathsf{W}$ such that any commutative square $\xymatrix{\bullet\ar[r]\ar[d]_{m}&\bullet\ar[d]^{w}\\ \bullet\ar[r]&\bullet}$ with $w\in\mathsf{W}$ allows to be factorized by a commutative diagram $\xymatrix{\bullet\ar[r]\ar[d]_{i}&\star\ar[d]^{w_{m}}\ar[r]&\bullet\ar[d]^{w}% \\ \bullet\ar[r]&\star\ar[r]&\bullet}$ with $w_{m}\in\mathsf{W}_{m}$. Let $I$ be a class of morphisms; $\mathsf{W}$ satisfies the solution set condition at $I$ if it satisfies it at each $m\in I$. If the solution set condition is satisfied for every $m\in\operatorname{mor}\mathcal{C}$, say simply that $\mathsf{W}$ satisfies the solution set condition.
Definition 1.14. (accessibility of a class of maps) Let $\mathcal{C}$ be a locally presentable category, $\mathsf{W}$ a class of morphisms of $\mathcal{C}$. Let $\operatorname{Mor}(\mathsf{W})$ and $\operatorname{Mor}(\mathcal{C})$ be as in remark 1.6. Say that $\mathsf{W}$ is an accessible class of maps3The last part of remark 1.6 applies here as well. if $\operatorname{Mor}(\mathsf{W})$ is an accessible category, and it is closed in $\operatorname{Mor}(\mathcal{C})$ under $\kappa$-filtered colimits for some $\kappa$.
Definition 1.1. Let $\mathcal{C}$ be a cocomplete category, $I$ any class of morphisms of $\mathcal{C}$. $\bullet$ Close the class of all pushouts of $I$ under transfinite composition. This defines the class $\mathsf{cell}(I)$ of relative $I$-cellular maps. $\bullet$ The class $\mathsf{cof}(I)$ of $I$-cofibrations is defined as follows: $X\stackrel{{\scriptstyle c}}{{\longrightarrow}}Y\in\mathsf{cof}(I)$ iff $c$ is a retract of an $X\stackrel{{\scriptstyle r}}{{\longrightarrow}}Z\in\mathsf{cell}(I)$ in the category $X/\mathcal{C}$ of objects under $X$. $\bullet$ $I$-fibrations, or $I$-injectives, denoted $\mathsf{inj}(I)$, are the morphisms with the right lifting property w.r.t. $I$; that is, such that in any commutative square $\xymatrix{\bullet\ar[d]_{i}\ar[r]&\bullet\ar[d]^{p}\\ \bullet\ar@{{}..>}[ur]\ar[r]&\bullet}$ with $i\in I$, $p\in\mathsf{inj}(I)$, a dotted lift making both triangles commute exists.
Definition 3.1 [38] A modular category is a pre-modular category satisfying the (equivalent) conditions of Corollary 2.16.
Definition 2.6 Let ${\cal C}$ be a braided tensor category and ${\cal K}$ a set of objects in ${\cal C}$, equivalently, a full subcategory of ${\cal C}$. Then we define the centralizer $C_{\cal C}({\cal K})$ of ${\cal K}$ in ${\cal C}$ (or relative commutant ${\cal C}\cap{\cal K}^{\prime}$) as the full subcategory defined by $\mbox{Obj}\,C_{\cal C}({\cal K})=\{X\in{\cal C}\ |\ c_{M}(X,Y)=\mbox{id}_{XY}% \ \ \forall Y\in{\cal K}\}.$
