Definition 2.1 The monodromy of two objects $X,Y$ in a tensor category with braiding $c$ is defined by $c_{M}(X,Y)=c(Y,X)\circ c(X,Y)\ \in\mbox{End}(XY).$
Definition 4.4 A modular category ${\cal C}$ is prime if every semisimple modular subcategory is equivalent either to ${\cal C}$ or the trivial modular category $\mbox{Vect}_{\mathbb{F}}$.
Definition 2.9 The center of a braided tensor category ${\cal C}$ is ${\cal Z}_{2}({\cal C})=C_{\cal C}({\cal C}).$ We say a semisimple braided tensor category has trivial center, if every object of ${\cal Z}_{2}({\cal C})$ is a direct sum of copies of the tensor unit ${\bf 1}$ or if, equivalently, every simple object in ${\cal Z}_{2}({\cal C})$ is isomorphic to ${\bf 1}$.
Definition 2.11 Let ${\cal C}$ be a semisimple ${\mathbb{F}}$-linear spherical category with $\mbox{End}({\bf 1})\cong{\mathbb{F}}$. If the set $\Gamma$ of isomorphism classes of simple objects is finite, the dimension of ${\cal C}$ is defined by $\dim{\cal C}=\sum_{X\in\Gamma}d(X)^{2},$ otherwise it is $\infty$.
3.4 Definition (). Let $\mathsf{U}$ and $\mathsf{V}$ be subcategories of $\mathsf{A}$. Denote by $\mathsf{K}^{\textnormal{R}}_{\mathsf{U}\textnormal{-tac}}(\mathsf{U}\cap% \mathsf{U}^{\perp})$ and $\mathsf{K}^{\textnormal{L}}_{\mathsf{V}\textnormal{-tac}}({}^{\perp}\mathsf{V}% \cap\mathsf{V})$ the homotopy categories of right $\mathsf{U}$-totally acyclic complexes and left $\mathsf{V}$-totally acyclic complexes. The subcategory $\mathsf{U}\cap\mathsf{U}^{\perp}$ is self-orthogonal, so the categories $\mathsf{K}^{\textnormal{R}}_{\smash{(\mathsf{U}\cap\mathsf{U}^{\perp})}% \textnormal{-tac}}(\mathsf{U}\cap\mathsf{U}^{\perp})$ and $\mathsf{K}^{\textnormal{L}}_{\smash{(\mathsf{U}\cap\mathsf{U}^{\perp})}% \textnormal{-tac}}(\mathsf{U}\cap\mathsf{U}^{\perp})$ coincide, see Proposition 1.5, and are denoted $\mathsf{K}_{\textnormal{tac}}(\mathsf{U}\cap\mathsf{U}^{\perp})$. The self-orthogonal subcategory ${}^{\perp}\mathsf{V}\cap\mathsf{V}$ similarly gives a category $\mathsf{K}_{\textnormal{tac}}({}^{\perp}\mathsf{V}\cap\mathsf{V})$. For a cotorsion pair $(\mathsf{U},\mathsf{V})$ all of these homotopy categories are $\mathsf{K}_{\textnormal{tac}}(\mathsf{U}\cap\mathsf{V})$.
1.6 Definition (). For a self-orthogonal subcategory $\mathsf{W}$ of $\mathsf{A}$, a right, equivalently left, $\mathsf{W}$-totally acyclic complex is simply called a $\mathsf{W}$-totally acyclic complex.
1.1 Definition (). Let $\mathsf{U}$ and $\mathsf{V}$ be subcategories of $\mathsf{A}$. (r) An $\mathsf{A}$-complex $T$ is called right $\mathsf{U}$-totally acyclic if the following hold: (1) $T$ is acyclic. (2) For each $i\in\mathbb{Z}$ the object $T_{i}$ belongs to $\mathsf{U}$. (3) For each $i\in\mathbb{Z}$ the object $\operatorname{Z}_{i}(T)$ belongs to $\mathsf{U}^{\perp}$. (4) For each $W\in\mathsf{U}\cap\mathsf{U}^{\perp}$ the complex $\operatorname{hom}_{\mathsf{A}}(T,W)$ is acyclic. (l) An $\mathsf{A}$-complex $T$ is called left $\mathsf{V}$-totally acyclic if the following hold: (1) $T$ is acyclic. (2) For each $i\in\mathbb{Z}$ the object $T_{i}$ belongs to $\mathsf{V}$. (3) For each $i\in\mathbb{Z}$ the object $\operatorname{Z}_{i}(T)$ belongs to ${}^{\perp}\mathsf{V}$. (4) For each $W\in{}^{\perp}\mathsf{V}\cap\mathsf{V}$ the complex $\operatorname{hom}_{\mathsf{A}}(W,T)$ is acyclic.
4.2 Definition (). A $\mathsf{FlatCot}(A)$-totally acyclic complex is called a totally acyclic complex of flat-cotorsion modules. A cycle module in such a complex, that is, a $\mathsf{FlatCot}(A)$-Gorenstein module, is called a Gorenstein flat-cotorsion module.
2.1 Definition (). Let $\mathsf{U}$ and $\mathsf{V}$ be subcategories of $\mathsf{A}$. (r) An object $M$ in $\mathsf{A}$ is called right $\mathsf{U}$-Gorenstein if there is a right $\mathsf{U}$-totally acyclic complex $T$ with $\operatorname{Z}_{0}(T)=M$. Denote by $\mathsf{RGor}_{\mathsf{U}}(\mathsf{A})$ the full subcategory of right $\mathsf{U}$-Gorenstein objects in $\mathsf{A}$. (l) An object $M$ in $\mathsf{A}$ is called left $\mathsf{V}$-Gorenstein if there is a left $\mathsf{V}$-totally acyclic complex $T$ with $\operatorname{Z}_{0}(T)=M$. Denote by $\mathsf{LGor}_{\mathsf{V}}(\mathsf{A})$ the full subcategory of left $\mathsf{V}$-Gorenstein objects in $\mathsf{A}$. For a self-orthogonal subcategory $\mathsf{W}$ one has $\mathsf{RGor}_{\mathsf{W}}(\mathsf{A})=\mathsf{LGor}_{\mathsf{W}}(\mathsf{A})$, see Proposition 1.5; this category is denoted $\mathsf{Gor}_{\mathsf{W}}(\mathsf{A})$, and its objects are called $\mathsf{W}$-Gorenstein.
Definition 2.2. We say that gradings (2.1) are (weakly) equivalent, if there exists an isomorphism $\varphi\colon A_{1}\mathrel{\widetilde{\to}}A_{2}$ of algebras such that for every $g_{1}\in G_{1}$ with $A_{1}^{(g_{1})}\neq 0$ there exists $g_{2}\in G_{2}$ such that $\varphi\left(A_{1}^{(g_{1})}\right)=A_{2}^{(g_{2})}$.
Definition 2.12. Let $\zeta\colon G\to\operatorname{Aut}(A)$ be an action of a group $G$ on an algebra $A$ and let $\varkappa_{\zeta}\colon G_{\zeta}\to\operatorname{Aut}(A)$ be an action of a group $G_{\zeta}$ equivalent to $\zeta$ via the identity isomorphism $\operatorname{id}_{A}$. We say that the pair $(G_{\zeta},\varkappa_{\zeta})$ is a universal group of the action $\zeta$ if for any other action $\zeta_{1}\colon G_{1}\to\operatorname{Aut}(A)$ equivalent to $\zeta$ via $\operatorname{id}_{A}$ there exists a unique group homomorphism $\varphi\colon G_{1}\to G_{\zeta}$ such that the following diagram is commutative: $\xymatrix{\operatorname{Aut}(A)&G_{\zeta}\ar[l]_{(}0.3){\varkappa_{\zeta}}\\ &G_{1}\ar[lu]^{\zeta_{1}}\ar@{-->}[u]_{\varphi}}$
Definition 2.4. Let $\Gamma$ be a group grading on an algebra $A$. Suppose that $\Gamma$ admits a realization as a $G_{\Gamma}$-grading for some group $G_{\Gamma}$. Denote by $\varkappa_{\Gamma}$ the corresponding embedding $\operatorname{supp}\Gamma\hookrightarrow G_{\Gamma}$. We say that $(G_{\Gamma},\varkappa_{\Gamma})$ is the universal group of the grading $\Gamma$ if for any realization of $\Gamma$ as a grading by a group $G$ with $\psi\colon\operatorname{supp}\Gamma\hookrightarrow G$ there exists a unique homomorphism $\varphi\colon G_{\Gamma}\to G$ such that the following diagram is commutative: $\xymatrix{\operatorname{supp}\Gamma\ar[r]^{(}0.6)\varkappa\ar[rd]_{\psi}&G_{% \Gamma}\ar@{-->}[d]^{\varphi}\\ &G}$
Definition 2.1 (e.g. [12, Definition 1.15]). Gradings (2.1) are isomorphic if $G_{1}=G_{2}$ and there exists an isomorphism $\varphi\colon A_{1}\mathrel{\widetilde{\to}}A_{2}$ of algebras such that $\varphi(A_{1}^{(g)})=A_{2}^{(g)}$ for all $g\in G_{1}$.
Definition 3.2. Given an $H$-comodule algebra $A$ with coaction $\rho\colon A\to A\otimes H$, call the coalgebra $C(\rho)$ constructed above the support coalgebra of the coaction $\rho$.
Definition 2.10. We say that actions $\zeta_{1}$ and $\zeta_{2}$ are equivalent via an isomorphism $\varphi$ if $\varphi\colon A_{1}\mathrel{\widetilde{\to}}A_{2}$ is an isomorphism of algebras such that $\tilde{\varphi}\Bigl{(}\langle\zeta_{1}\bigl{(}G_{1}\bigr{)}\rangle_{F}\Bigr{)% }=\langle\zeta_{2}\bigl{(}G_{2}\bigr{)}\rangle_{F}$ where the $F$-linear span $\langle\cdot\rangle_{F}$ is taken in the corresponding $\operatorname{End}(A_{i})$ and the isomorphism $\tilde{\varphi}\colon\operatorname{End}_{F}(A_{1})\mathrel{\widetilde{\to}}% \operatorname{End}_{F}(A_{2})$ is defined by $\tilde{\varphi}(\psi)(a)=\varphi\Bigl{(}\psi\bigl{(}\varphi^{-1}(a)\bigr{)}% \Bigr{)}$ for $\psi\in\operatorname{End}_{F}(A_{1})$ and $a\in A_{2}$.
Definition 4.1. Let $A_{i}$ be $H_{i}$-module algebras for Hopf algebras $H_{i}$, $i=1,2$. We say that an isomorphism $\varphi\colon A_{1}\mathrel{\widetilde{\to}}A_{2}$ of algebras is a support equivalence of module algebra structures on $A_{1}$ and $A_{2}$ if $\tilde{\varphi}\Bigl{(}\zeta_{1}\bigl{(}H_{1}\bigr{)}\Bigr{)}=\zeta_{2}\bigl{(% }H_{2}\bigr{)}$ where $\zeta_{i}$ is the module algebra structure on $A_{i}$ and the isomorphism $\tilde{\varphi}\colon\operatorname{End}_{F}(A_{1})\mathrel{\widetilde{\to}}% \operatorname{End}_{F}(A_{2})$ is defined by the conjugation by $\varphi$. In this case we call module algebra structures on $A_{1}$ and $A_{2}$ support equivalent via the isomorphism $\varphi$ and, as in the comodule algebra case, we will say just equivalent for short.
Definition 3.1. Let $A_{i}$ be (not necessarily associative) $H_{i}$-comodule algebras for Hopf algebras $H_{i}$, $i=1,2$. We say that comodule structures on $A_{1}$ and $A_{2}$ are support equivalent via the algebra isomorphism $\varphi\colon A_{1}\mathrel{\widetilde{\to}}A_{2}$ if $\tilde{\varphi}\Bigl{(}\zeta_{1}\bigl{(}H_{1}^{*}\bigr{)}\Bigr{)}=\zeta_{2}% \bigl{(}H_{2}^{*}\bigr{)}$ where $\zeta_{i}$ is the algebra homomorphism $H_{i}^{*}\to\operatorname{End}_{F}(A_{i})$ induced by the comodule algebra structure on $A_{i}$ and the isomorphism $\tilde{\varphi}\colon\operatorname{End}_{F}(A_{1})\mathrel{\widetilde{\to}}% \operatorname{End}_{F}(A_{2})$ is defined by $\tilde{\varphi}(\psi)(a)=\varphi\Bigl{(}\psi\bigl{(}\varphi^{-1}(a)\bigr{)}% \Bigr{)}$ for $\psi\in\operatorname{End}_{F}(A_{1})$ and $a\in A_{2}$. As the only equivalences we will consider in the sequel are support equivalences, we will use the term just equivalence.
Definition 2. The decorated marked surface ${\mathbf{S}}_{\bigtriangleup}$ is a marked surface $\mathbf{S}$ together with a fixed set $\bigtriangleup$ of $\aleph$ ‘decorating’ points in $\mathbf{S}^{\circ}$.
Definition 8 (Bridgeland). A stability condition $\sigma=(Z,\mathcal{P})$ on a triangulated category $\operatorname{\mathcal{D}}$ consists of a central charge $Z\in\operatorname{Hom}_{\mathbb{Z}}(K(\operatorname{\mathcal{D}}),\mathbb{C})$ and a collection of full additive subcategories $\{\mathcal{P}(\varphi)\subset\operatorname{\mathcal{D}}\mid\varphi\in\mathbb{R}\}$, such that • if $0\neq E\in\mathcal{P}(\varphi)$ then $Z(E)=m(E)\exp(\varphi\pi\mathbf{i})$ for some $m(E)\in\mathbb{R}_{>0}$; • $\mathcal{P}(\varphi+1)=\mathcal{P}(\varphi)[1]$, for all $\varphi\in\mathbb{R}$; • if $\varphi_{1}>\varphi_{2}$, then $\operatorname{Hom}(\mathcal{P}(\varphi_{1}),\mathcal{P}(\varphi_{2}))=0$; • any object $E\in\operatorname{\mathcal{D}}$ admits a Harder-Narashimhan filtration of triangles (cf. [Q1, (8.1)]), whose factors are $A_{j}\in\mathcal{P}(\varphi_{j})$ for $\leq j\leq m$ satisfying $\varphi_{1}>\varphi_{2}>...>\varphi_{m}$.
Definition 6. The decorated real blow-up $\mathbf{X}^{\phi}_{\bigtriangleup}$ of $(\mathbf{X},\phi)$ is the decorated marked surface obtained from $\mathbf{X}^{\phi}$ by adding the set of zeroes of $\phi$ as decorations. Given any decorated marked surface ${\mathbf{S}}_{\bigtriangleup}$, an ${\mathbf{S}}_{\bigtriangleup}$-framed quadratic differential $(\mathbf{X},\phi,\psi)$ is a Riemann surface $\mathbf{X}$ with a GMN differential $\phi$, equipped with a diffeomorphism $\psi\colon{\mathbf{S}}_{\bigtriangleup}\to\mathbf{X}^{\phi}_{\bigtriangleup}$, preserving the marked points and decorations (see right picture of Figure 3).. Two ${\mathbf{S}}_{\bigtriangleup}$-framed quadratic differentials $(\mathbf{X}_{1},\phi_{1},\psi_{1})$ and $(\mathbf{X}_{2},\phi_{2},\psi_{2})$ are equivalent, if there exists a biholomorphism $f\colon\mathbf{X}_{1}\to\mathbf{X}_{2}$ such that $f^{*}(\phi_{2})=\phi_{1}$ and furthermore $\psi_{2}^{-1}\circ f_{*}\circ\psi_{1}\in\operatorname{Diff}_{0}({\mathbf{S}}_{% \bigtriangleup})$, where $f_{*}\colon\mathbf{X}_{1}^{\phi_{1}}\to\mathbf{X}_{2}^{\phi_{2}}$ is the induced diffeomorphism. Here $\operatorname{Diff}_{0}({\mathbf{S}}_{\bigtriangleup})$ is the identity component of the group $\operatorname{Diff}({\mathbf{S}}_{\bigtriangleup})$ of diffeomorphisms preserving marked points and decorations (each setwise).
Definitions 3.2. 1) $S/R$ is h-separable if the functor $\varphi_{\ast}:S$-$\mathrm{Mod}\rightarrow R$-$\mathrm{Mod}$ is h-separable. 2) A heavy separability idempotent (h-separability idempotent for short) of $S/R$ is an element $\sum_{i}a_{i}\otimes_{R}b_{i}\in S\otimes_{R}S$ such that $\sum_{i}a_{i}\otimes_{R}b_{i}$ is a separability idempotent, i.e. $\sum_{i}a_{i}b_{i}=1,\qquad\sum_{i}sa_{i}\otimes_{R}b_{i}=\sum_{i}a_{i}\otimes% _{R}b_{i}s\quad\text{ for every }s\in S,$ which moreover fulfills $\sum_{i,j}a_{i}\otimes_{R}b_{i}a_{j}\otimes_{R}b_{j}=\sum_{i}a_{i}\otimes_{R}1% _{S}\otimes_{R}b_{i}.$
Definition 1.1. For every functor $F:\mathcal{B}\rightarrow\mathcal{A}$ we set $F_{X,Y}:\mathrm{Hom}_{\mathcal{B}}\left(X,Y\right)\rightarrow\mathrm{Hom}_{% \mathcal{A}}\left(FX,FY\right):f\mapsto Ff$ Recall that $F$ is called separable if there is a natural transformation $P_{-,-}:=P_{-,-}^{F}:\mathrm{Hom}_{\mathcal{A}}\left(F-,F-\right)\rightarrow% \mathrm{Hom}_{\mathcal{B}}\left(-,-\right)$ such that $P_{X,Y}\circ F_{X,Y}=\mathrm{Id}$ for every $X,Y$ objects in $\mathcal{B}$. We say that $F$ is heavily separable (h-separable for short) if it is separable and the $P_{X,Y}$’s make commutative the following diagram for every $X,Y,Z\in\mathcal{B}.$ $\xymatrixcolsep{1.5cm}\xymatrixrowsep{0.7cm}\xymatrix{\mathrm{Hom}_{\mathcal{A% }}\left(FX,FY\right)\times\mathrm{Hom}_{\mathcal{A}}\left(FY,FZ\right)\ar[rr]^% {P_{X,Y}\times P_{Y,Z}}\ar[d]_{\circ}&&\mathrm{Hom}_{\mathcal{B}}\left(X,Y% \right)\times\mathrm{Hom}_{\mathcal{B}}\left(Y,Z\right)\ar[d]^{\circ}\\ \mathrm{Hom}_{\mathcal{A}}\left(FX,FZ\right)\ar[rr]^{P_{X,Z}}&&\mathrm{Hom}_{% \mathcal{B}}\left(X,Z\right)}$ Invisible (To be hidden): $\begin{array}[]{ccc}\mathrm{Hom}_{\mathcal{A}}\left(FX,FY\right)\times\mathrm{% Hom}_{\mathcal{A}}\left(FY,FZ\right)&\overset{P_{X,Y}\times P_{Y,Z}}{% \longrightarrow}&\mathrm{Hom}_{\mathcal{B}}\left(X,Y\right)\times\mathrm{Hom}_% {\mathcal{B}}\left(Y,Z\right)\\ \circ\downarrow&&\downarrow\circ\\ \mathrm{Hom}_{\mathcal{A}}\left(FX,FZ\right)&\overset{P_{X,Z}}{\longrightarrow% }&\mathrm{Hom}_{\mathcal{B}}\left(X,Z\right)\end{array}$ where the vertical arrows are the obvious compositions. On elements the above diagram means that $P_{X,Z}(f\circ g)=P_{Y,Z}(f)\circ P_{X,Y}(g).$
Definition 2.6. Following [LMW, Section 4] we say that a grouplike morphism for a comonad $\left(C,\Delta:C\rightarrow CC,\epsilon:C\rightarrow\mathrm{Id}\right)$ is a natural transformation $\delta:\mathrm{Id}\rightarrow C$ such that $\epsilon\circ\delta=\mathrm{Id}$ and $\delta\delta=\Delta\circ\delta.$ Dually an augmentation for a monad $\left(M,m:MM\rightarrow M,\eta:\mathrm{Id}\rightarrow M\right)$ is a natural transformation $\gamma:M\rightarrow\mathrm{Id}$ such that $\gamma\circ\eta=\mathrm{Id}$ and $\gamma\gamma=\gamma\circ m.$
Definition 0.1. A strongly central filtration $G_{*}$ is a nested sequence of groups $G_{1}\supseteq G_{2}\supseteq G_{3}\cdots$ such that $[G_{i},G_{j}]\subseteq G_{i+j}$ for all $i,j\geqslant 1$. These filtrations are the objects of a category $\mathcal{SCF}$, where morphisms from $G_{*}$ to $H_{*}$ are those group morphisms from $G_{1}$ to $H_{1}$ sending each $G_{i}$ into $H_{i}$.
Definition 2.2. The center of ${\sf A}$ is the set of global sections of $\sf p:{\sf Z}{\sf A}\rightarrow{\sf A}$.
